on": "NONE", "active_lock_reason": null, "body": "I tried running [this code](https://play.rust-lang.org/?version=stable&mode=debug&edition=2018&gist=b1a3f474bbde1333e0b5ee1a3d5af28f):\r\n\r\n```rust\r\nuse num::range;\r\n\r\nfn main() {\r\n    let (start, end) = (0.01, 128.99);\r\n\r\n    for n in range(start, end) {\r\n        println!(\"{}\", n);\r\n    }\r\n}\r\n\r\n```\r\n\r\nI expected to see this happen: \r\nI expected to... well, I'm not too sure.\r\nIf I would've used `start = 0.1` instead of `start = 0.01` it would've printed all numbers, beginning in `start`, in increments of 1.0, up until `end` (non-inclusive range).\r\nUsing `let (start, end) = (0.1, 128.99);` I get:\r\n\r\n```\r\n  \u22ee\r\n13.01\r\n14.01\r\n15.01\r\n16.01\r\n17.01\r\n18.01\r\n  \u22ee\r\n```\r\n\r\nI guess I would've expected it to perform the same, even though floats are known to be wonky.\r\n \r\nInstead, this happened:\r\nAs you can see, it just prints the list of numbers but the accuracy after the decimal point differs on 2^x:\r\n- 0-15 end with `.01`\r\n- 16-31 end with `.009999999999998`\r\n- 32-63 end with `.01`\r\n- 64-127 end with `.009999999999998`\r\n\r\n### Meta\r\nIt behaves the same in both `Stable` and `Nightly`.\r\nI'm not sure whether it's a bug, and if it is, I am not sure whether it's in `rustc` or rather in the `num` crate. \r\n\r\n`rustc --version --verbose`:\r\n```\r\nrustc 1.50.0-nightly (bb178237c 2020-12-25)\r\nbinary: rustc\r\ncommit-hash: bb178237c5539c75e1b85ab78a8ab902b1f333d5\r\ncommit-date: 2020-12-25\r\nhost: x86_64-unknown-linux-gnu\r\nrelease: 1.50.0-nightly\r\n```\r\n\r\n<!--\r\nInclude a backtrace in the code block by setting `RUST_BACKTRACE=1` in your\r\nenvironment. E.g. `RUST_BACKTRACE=1 cargo build`.\r\n-->\r\n<details><summary>Backtrace</summary>\r\n<p>\r\n\r\n```\r\n\u276f RUST_BACKTRACE=1 cargo build\r\n    Finished dev [unoptimized + debuginfo] target(s) in 0.01s\r\n\r\n```\r\n\r\n</p>\r\n</details>\r\n", "closed_by": {"login": "Mark-Simula